00:18:19.186 --> 00:18:20.406 A:middle
The computer player is

00:18:20.406 --> 00:18:21.306 A:middle
completely random.

00:18:21.436 --> 00:18:23.116 A:middle
So it's just possible it's going

00:18:23.116 --> 00:18:23.876 A:middle
to beat me today.

00:18:24.516 --> 00:18:28.066 A:middle
[ Laughter ]

00:18:28.566 --> 00:18:29.916 A:middle
So I've shown you how we can

00:18:29.916 --> 00:18:31.046 A:middle
execute some of the lines of

00:18:31.086 --> 00:18:33.066 A:middle
code and then step-by-step

00:18:33.586 --> 00:18:34.786 A:middle
execute lines of code which are

00:18:34.786 --> 00:18:35.546 A:middle
already present in the

00:18:35.546 --> 00:18:36.076 A:middle
playground.

00:18:36.076 --> 00:18:37.996 A:middle
But we can do more than that.

00:18:37.996 --> 00:18:39.706 A:middle
It's always safe to add new code

00:18:39.706 --> 00:18:40.706 A:middle
at the end of a playground.

00:18:41.126 --> 00:18:41.976 A:middle
So let's make another move.

00:18:51.456 --> 00:18:52.246 A:middle
There we go.

00:18:52.736 --> 00:18:54.626 A:middle
Now, I can click the Play button

00:18:55.216 --> 00:19:00.026 A:middle
to execute this line of code and

00:18:55.216 --> 00:19:00.026 A:middle
to execute this line of code and

00:19:00.026 --> 00:19:00.856 A:middle
I think now we'll let the

00:19:00.856 --> 00:19:01.746 A:middle
computer have another go.

00:19:07.196 --> 00:19:07.976 A:middle
That's great.

00:19:08.516 --> 00:19:12.626 A:middle
[ Laughing ]

00:19:13.126 --> 00:19:14.166 A:middle
You should notice a couple of

00:19:14.166 --> 00:19:14.676 A:middle
things here.

00:19:15.296 --> 00:19:17.686 A:middle
Number one, in the beginning the

00:19:17.686 --> 00:19:18.616 A:middle
board was flat.

00:19:18.616 --> 00:19:20.106 A:middle
I had to rotate it so it was in

00:19:20.106 --> 00:19:21.236 A:middle
a position where we could view

00:19:21.236 --> 00:19:21.436 A:middle
it.

00:19:23.506 --> 00:19:24.906 A:middle
As we execute more lines of

00:19:24.946 --> 00:19:26.846 A:middle
code, it doesn't rotate back to

00:19:26.846 --> 00:19:27.896 A:middle
its original position.

00:19:28.356 --> 00:19:29.846 A:middle
This is pretty good because I

00:19:29.846 --> 00:19:31.366 A:middle
could write lines of code to

00:19:31.366 --> 00:19:32.456 A:middle
rotate it to the correct

00:19:32.456 --> 00:19:33.976 A:middle
position, but this would involve

00:19:33.976 --> 00:19:34.506 A:middle
something called [inaudible],

00:19:34.556 --> 00:19:36.316 A:middle
and I don't think I'm quite

00:19:36.316 --> 00:19:37.866 A:middle
ready to learn that yet.

00:19:38.756 --> 00:19:41.086 A:middle
The second reason it's good is

00:19:41.086 --> 00:19:42.836 A:middle
because if the computer player

00:19:42.836 --> 00:19:45.196 A:middle
was allowed to play again, every

00:19:45.196 --> 00:19:47.456 A:middle
time we executed new code it

00:19:47.456 --> 00:19:48.846 A:middle
would effectively get a do-over,

00:19:48.926 --> 00:19:50.036 A:middle
which would be a little unfair.

00:19:51.556 --> 00:19:52.376 A:middle
Let's finish this up.

00:19:52.426 --> 00:19:53.656 A:middle
I think I can take the game home

00:19:53.656 --> 00:19:55.000 A:middle
from here.

00:20:04.436 --> 00:20:08.156 A:middle
Is that the right move?

00:20:08.726 --> 00:20:09.616 A:middle
That's great.

00:20:10.516 --> 00:20:16.886 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:20:17.386 --> 00:20:18.376 A:middle
You can see the game has

00:20:18.376 --> 00:20:20.126 A:middle
highlighted my winning move by

00:20:20.126 --> 00:20:21.826 A:middle
placing three red circles.

00:20:23.196 --> 00:20:24.276 A:middle
That's not too fancy.

00:20:24.276 --> 00:20:25.356 A:middle
I'm looking for something which

00:20:25.356 --> 00:20:26.316 A:middle
really makes it feel like a

00:20:26.316 --> 00:20:27.066 A:middle
celebration.

00:20:27.436 --> 00:20:29.126 A:middle
So I've been working on a new

00:20:29.126 --> 00:20:30.146 A:middle
version of the UI.

00:20:30.956 --> 00:20:32.446 A:middle
In a traditional development

00:20:32.446 --> 00:20:33.806 A:middle
environment, you would have to

00:20:33.806 --> 00:20:35.426 A:middle
set up a complex harness to

00:20:35.426 --> 00:20:37.156 A:middle
automatically play you deep into

00:20:37.156 --> 00:20:39.446 A:middle
the game or whatever the API was

00:20:39.446 --> 00:20:41.186 A:middle
you were using so that we could

00:20:41.186 --> 00:20:42.556 A:middle
test out something that happened

00:20:43.156 --> 00:20:44.306 A:middle
later on in the program.

00:20:45.306 --> 00:20:46.636 A:middle
But in a playground, because I'm

00:20:46.636 --> 00:20:48.636 A:middle
able to execute step-by-step, I

00:20:48.636 --> 00:20:49.986 A:middle
can play it manually to the end

00:20:49.986 --> 00:20:51.356 A:middle
of the game and then write new

00:20:51.356 --> 00:20:52.916 A:middle
lines of code to update

00:20:53.336 --> 00:20:54.426 A:middle
whatever's going on at that

00:20:54.426 --> 00:20:54.696 A:middle
point.

00:20:55.356 --> 00:20:56.206 A:middle
Let's do that now.

00:21:01.316 --> 00:21:03.216 A:middle
I've prepared a new effect for

00:21:03.216 --> 00:21:04.176 A:middle
the end of the game using a

00:21:04.176 --> 00:21:05.046 A:middle
particle system.

00:21:06.506 --> 00:21:07.866 A:middle
Let's use Shift Return to

00:21:07.866 --> 00:21:08.546 A:middle
execute it.

00:21:09.626 --> 00:21:12.216 A:middle
Boom. And that feels much more

00:21:12.216 --> 00:21:12.806 A:middle
like a win.

00:21:14.516 --> 00:21:17.566 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:21:18.066 --> 00:21:19.486 A:middle
So let's review what we've just

00:21:19.486 --> 00:21:19.706 A:middle
seen.

00:21:20.736 --> 00:21:22.956 A:middle
By running step-by-step we can

00:21:22.956 --> 00:21:24.956 A:middle
explore an idea a line at a

00:21:24.956 --> 00:21:25.446 A:middle
time.

00:21:26.356 --> 00:21:27.416 A:middle
This enables us to have a

00:21:27.416 --> 00:21:29.756 A:middle
conversation between code and

00:21:29.756 --> 00:21:30.146 A:middle
data.

00:21:30.756 --> 00:21:32.596 A:middle
Every time we learn a new fact

00:21:32.886 --> 00:21:34.536 A:middle
we can write the next line of

00:21:34.536 --> 00:21:36.416 A:middle
code to explore it a little

00:21:36.416 --> 00:21:36.736 A:middle
more.

00:21:37.706 --> 00:21:39.506 A:middle
We can use Shift Return to keep

00:21:39.506 --> 00:21:41.216 A:middle
our hands on the keyboard and

00:21:41.216 --> 00:21:42.306 A:middle
our brains in the zone.

00:21:43.246 --> 00:21:45.536 A:middle
And finally, by adding a dynamic

00:21:45.536 --> 00:21:47.376 A:middle
live view to a playground, we

00:21:47.376 --> 00:21:48.966 A:middle
can create a second view of our

00:21:48.966 --> 00:21:50.616 A:middle
model and we can seamlessly

00:21:50.616 --> 00:21:52.786 A:middle
shift between manipulating it in

00:21:52.786 --> 00:21:54.556 A:middle
a graphical environment and

00:21:54.556 --> 00:21:55.286 A:middle
using code.

00:21:56.556 --> 00:21:59.356 A:middle
So whether you're a beginner,

00:21:59.706 --> 00:22:02.436 A:middle
just learning about new Apple

00:21:59.706 --> 00:22:02.436 A:middle
just learning about new Apple

00:22:02.436 --> 00:22:05.316 A:middle
APIs or an experienced

00:22:05.376 --> 00:22:07.846 A:middle
programmer trying to sketch out

00:22:07.906 --> 00:22:09.806 A:middle
the bones of their next great

00:22:10.616 --> 00:22:13.426 A:middle
app, the next time you have a

00:22:13.476 --> 00:22:16.056 A:middle
coding inspiration we invite you

00:22:16.056 --> 00:22:17.536 A:middle
to get started with a

00:22:17.536 --> 00:22:18.186 A:middle
playground.

00:22:18.656 --> 00:22:23.126 A:middle
Just in case you're still

00:22:23.126 --> 00:22:25.536 A:middle
looking for ideas I've got three

00:22:25.536 --> 00:22:26.086 A:middle
right here.

00:22:27.116 --> 00:22:29.446 A:middle
Number one if you're creating

00:22:29.446 --> 00:22:31.696 A:middle
your own API, one of the best

00:22:31.696 --> 00:22:33.716 A:middle
ways to showcase it is to create

00:22:33.716 --> 00:22:35.976 A:middle
a follow along tutorial for your

00:22:35.976 --> 00:22:36.146 A:middle
API.

00:22:36.366 --> 00:22:37.956 A:middle
Users can execute the code

00:22:37.996 --> 00:22:40.006 A:middle
step-by-step and see in real

00:22:40.006 --> 00:22:42.586 A:middle
time what it does.

00:22:43.316 --> 00:22:45.566 A:middle
Number two you can download and

00:22:45.566 --> 00:22:47.176 A:middle
explore some publicly available

00:22:47.176 --> 00:22:48.976 A:middle
data using the playground

00:22:48.976 --> 00:22:52.016 A:middle
step-by-step to drill down into

00:22:52.016 --> 00:22:52.586 A:middle
your data.

00:22:53.816 --> 00:22:55.806 A:middle
You could get this from maps,

00:22:56.226 --> 00:22:57.586 A:middle
from local government, or

00:22:57.586 --> 00:22:59.326 A:middle
perhaps a class project.

00:23:00.256 --> 00:23:03.036 A:middle
Finally, like I did, you could

00:23:03.036 --> 00:23:04.976 A:middle
create a game or an animation.

00:23:05.836 --> 00:23:09.286 A:middle
Start off simple using SpriteKit

00:23:09.356 --> 00:23:11.476 A:middle
or SyncKit and line by line

00:23:11.476 --> 00:23:13.346 A:middle
enhance it until it's completely

00:23:13.346 --> 00:23:13.606 A:middle
awesome.

00:23:14.166 --> 00:23:18.106 A:middle
So I hope we've shown you today

00:23:18.616 --> 00:23:20.626 A:middle
that playgrounds are not a toy.

00:23:21.146 --> 00:23:23.156 A:middle
They're fun but they're serious

00:23:23.156 --> 00:23:23.466 A:middle
fun.

00:23:26.726 --> 00:23:28.296 A:middle
They allow you to explore code

00:23:28.296 --> 00:23:30.006 A:middle
and data interactively.

00:23:30.726 --> 00:23:31.766 A:middle
This is great whether you've

00:23:31.766 --> 00:23:33.356 A:middle
downloaded an unknown snippet of

00:23:33.356 --> 00:23:35.246 A:middle
JSON using a rest API from the

00:23:35.246 --> 00:23:37.176 A:middle
Internet, or if you're dealing

00:23:37.176 --> 00:23:38.576 A:middle
with hundreds of thousands or

00:23:38.576 --> 00:23:40.886 A:middle
millions of lines of data for a

00:23:40.886 --> 00:23:42.236 A:middle
machine learning application.

00:23:42.516 --> 00:23:44.026 A:middle
And to find out more about that

00:23:44.026 --> 00:23:45.486 A:middle
use case I encourage you to

00:23:45.486 --> 00:23:47.256 A:middle
download and watch the Create ML

00:23:47.256 --> 00:23:49.796 A:middle
sessions in your WWDC

00:23:49.796 --> 00:23:50.526 A:middle
application.

00:23:52.006 --> 00:23:53.466 A:middle
Secondly there's really no

00:23:53.466 --> 00:23:55.236 A:middle
better way to learn how to use

00:23:55.236 --> 00:23:56.316 A:middle
Apple APIs.

00:23:56.906 --> 00:23:57.736 A:middle
Whether you're just getting

00:23:57.736 --> 00:23:59.946 A:middle
started or your trying out a new

00:23:59.946 --> 00:24:02.806 A:middle
API, which you've learned about

00:23:59.946 --> 00:24:02.806 A:middle
API, which you've learned about

00:24:03.436 --> 00:24:04.606 A:middle
at this WWDC.

00:24:04.996 --> 00:24:06.436 A:middle
You don't just have to use

00:24:06.436 --> 00:24:07.156 A:middle
Apple's APIs.

00:24:07.946 --> 00:24:09.546 A:middle
You can also import your own

00:24:09.546 --> 00:24:11.016 A:middle
frameworks into playgrounds.

00:24:11.346 --> 00:24:12.436 A:middle
And one of the best ways to

00:24:12.436 --> 00:24:14.666 A:middle
showcase this is to create

00:24:14.666 --> 00:24:16.146 A:middle
custom representations of your

00:24:16.146 --> 00:24:18.546 A:middle
data types allowing developers

00:24:18.936 --> 00:24:20.036 A:middle
to view the most relevant

00:24:20.036 --> 00:24:21.556 A:middle
information at a glance.

00:24:22.046 --> 00:24:24.216 A:middle
And to talk more about these two

00:24:24.216 --> 00:24:26.166 A:middle
advanced concepts, I'd like to

00:24:26.166 --> 00:24:27.616 A:middle
invite TJ to the stage.

00:24:29.516 --> 00:24:36.546 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:24:37.046 --> 00:24:37.936 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Thank you, Alex.

00:24:38.276 --> 00:24:40.476 A:middle
My name is TJ Usiyan and I'm an

00:24:40.476 --> 00:24:41.286 A:middle
Xcode Engineer.

00:24:42.126 --> 00:24:43.546 A:middle
By the time I finish my section,

00:24:43.866 --> 00:24:45.096 A:middle
I'm sure that all of you will

00:24:45.096 --> 00:24:47.216 A:middle
agree that every librarian

00:24:47.216 --> 00:24:49.266 A:middle
framework that you ship will and

00:24:49.266 --> 00:24:50.916 A:middle
can be improved with the

00:24:50.916 --> 00:24:52.166 A:middle
addition of a playground.

00:24:53.586 --> 00:24:55.976 A:middle
Playgrounds provide a richer

00:24:56.166 --> 00:24:58.616 A:middle
experience when providing

00:24:58.616 --> 00:25:01.236 A:middle
readme's, tutorials, and general

00:24:58.616 --> 00:25:01.236 A:middle
readme's, tutorials, and general

00:25:01.236 --> 00:25:02.856 A:middle
API documentation.

00:25:03.936 --> 00:25:06.556 A:middle
One of the ways that they can do

00:25:06.556 --> 00:25:08.686 A:middle
this is by, as Alex said,

00:25:08.866 --> 00:25:09.926 A:middle
providing your own

00:25:09.926 --> 00:25:11.926 A:middle
representation in playgrounds.

00:25:12.436 --> 00:25:14.116 A:middle
I'm going to cover all of these

00:25:14.116 --> 00:25:16.656 A:middle
things starting with Custom

00:25:16.656 --> 00:25:18.236 A:middle
Playground Display Convertible,

00:25:18.746 --> 00:25:20.636 A:middle
which will allow you to provide

00:25:20.716 --> 00:25:22.906 A:middle
custom representations of your

00:25:23.596 --> 00:25:25.956 A:middle
types in playgrounds so that

00:25:25.956 --> 00:25:27.776 A:middle
users can get a nice summary.

00:25:27.886 --> 00:25:31.016 A:middle
I'll follow that up with how to

00:25:31.016 --> 00:25:33.646 A:middle
import your frameworks into

00:25:34.056 --> 00:25:34.766 A:middle
playgrounds.

00:25:35.766 --> 00:25:37.476 A:middle
And finally, I'll cover a little

00:25:37.476 --> 00:25:38.746 A:middle
bit of troubleshooting tips for

00:25:38.746 --> 00:25:40.156 A:middle
when things don't go exactly as

00:25:40.156 --> 00:25:40.776 A:middle
you'd expect.

00:25:43.616 --> 00:25:45.426 A:middle
Let's start with Playground

00:25:45.646 --> 00:25:46.526 A:middle
Display Convertible.

00:25:47.866 --> 00:25:50.816 A:middle
So as you know, when a user

00:25:51.106 --> 00:25:54.256 A:middle
types in a line of code values

00:25:54.256 --> 00:25:56.726 A:middle
show up on the right hand side

00:25:56.726 --> 00:25:57.736 A:middle
in the result sidebar.

00:25:58.876 --> 00:26:01.256 A:middle
For types that are no optimized

00:25:58.876 --> 00:26:01.256 A:middle
For types that are no optimized

00:26:01.256 --> 00:26:03.466 A:middle
for playgrounds there are two

00:26:03.466 --> 00:26:04.716 A:middle
ways that playgrounds will

00:26:04.716 --> 00:26:05.976 A:middle
generate this description.

00:26:06.956 --> 00:26:09.296 A:middle
For types that do not conform to

00:26:09.296 --> 00:26:12.236 A:middle
Custom String Convertible, we

00:26:13.026 --> 00:26:14.666 A:middle
will create a structured

00:26:14.666 --> 00:26:16.686 A:middle
representation using the Swift

00:26:16.686 --> 00:26:16.856 A:middle
type.

00:26:17.306 --> 00:26:19.436 A:middle
For types that do conform to

00:26:19.436 --> 00:26:20.746 A:middle
Custom String Convertible, we

00:26:20.746 --> 00:26:23.256 A:middle
will use the result of calling

00:26:23.256 --> 00:26:23.806 A:middle
descriptions.

00:26:24.276 --> 00:26:27.906 A:middle
When this isn't enough sometimes

00:26:27.906 --> 00:26:31.716 A:middle
your users will tap on the Quick

00:26:31.716 --> 00:26:33.236 A:middle
Look button on the right-hand

00:26:33.236 --> 00:26:33.576 A:middle
side.

00:26:35.416 --> 00:26:40.026 A:middle
They will also tap or click on

00:26:40.026 --> 00:26:42.646 A:middle
the Inline Results button.

00:26:43.736 --> 00:26:47.636 A:middle
When they do this a custom

00:26:47.636 --> 00:26:49.316 A:middle
representation will show up.

00:26:49.316 --> 00:26:51.556 A:middle
Often a textual representation.

00:26:52.676 --> 00:26:54.566 A:middle
And for many types this is

00:26:54.566 --> 00:26:56.106 A:middle
perfectly enough but sometimes

00:26:56.206 --> 00:26:58.896 A:middle
maybe you would like to return a

00:26:58.896 --> 00:26:59.236 A:middle
number.

00:27:00.816 --> 00:27:03.336 A:middle
This is still text though and

00:27:03.336 --> 00:27:06.056 A:middle
there are times when text isn't

00:27:06.056 --> 00:27:07.066 A:middle
going to be enough and you would

00:27:07.066 --> 00:27:08.456 A:middle
like to return something

00:27:08.456 --> 00:27:10.446 A:middle
graphical, maybe a picture.

00:27:12.136 --> 00:27:14.656 A:middle
The way to control what you

00:27:14.656 --> 00:27:17.706 A:middle
return is to implement Custom

00:27:17.706 --> 00:27:19.226 A:middle
Playground Display Convertible,

00:27:20.106 --> 00:27:22.936 A:middle
a new protocol introduced in

00:27:22.936 --> 00:27:26.506 A:middle
Xcode 9.3 and Swift 4.1.

00:27:27.256 --> 00:27:29.436 A:middle
It replaces Custom Playground

00:27:29.436 --> 00:27:31.046 A:middle
Quick Lookable, which was

00:27:31.046 --> 00:27:32.686 A:middle
deprecated in the same versions.

00:27:33.026 --> 00:27:36.756 A:middle
Let's take a look at conformance

00:27:36.756 --> 00:27:39.016 A:middle
right now.

00:27:40.086 --> 00:27:41.926 A:middle
You can see here that conforming

00:27:41.926 --> 00:27:44.356 A:middle
involves only returning one

00:27:44.356 --> 00:27:45.426 A:middle
property, Playground

00:27:45.426 --> 00:27:45.856 A:middle
Description.

00:27:46.546 --> 00:27:47.946 A:middle
Playground Description is of

00:27:47.946 --> 00:27:49.916 A:middle
type Any, which means you can

00:27:49.916 --> 00:27:51.456 A:middle
return anything that you feel

00:27:51.456 --> 00:27:54.686 A:middle
best describes your value.

00:27:56.496 --> 00:27:58.256 A:middle
Now, there are certain types

00:27:58.256 --> 00:27:59.416 A:middle
that have specialized

00:27:59.416 --> 00:28:01.446 A:middle
representations already and

00:27:59.416 --> 00:28:01.446 A:middle
representations already and

00:28:01.446 --> 00:28:04.296 A:middle
those are provided by Apple.

00:28:04.506 --> 00:28:06.856 A:middle
Here's a list of the types with

00:28:06.856 --> 00:28:08.716 A:middle
specialized representations as

00:28:08.716 --> 00:28:11.786 A:middle
of Xcode 9.3 and Swift 4.1.

00:28:12.616 --> 00:28:14.676 A:middle
The types on the left have a

00:28:14.676 --> 00:28:15.936 A:middle
particularly textual

00:28:15.936 --> 00:28:16.766 A:middle
representation.

00:28:17.426 --> 00:28:19.456 A:middle
The types on the right have a

00:28:19.456 --> 00:28:20.646 A:middle
graphical representation.

00:28:21.056 --> 00:28:23.586 A:middle
I invite you to try each of

00:28:23.586 --> 00:28:25.686 A:middle
these and decide which best

00:28:25.686 --> 00:28:27.326 A:middle
represents your value in a

00:28:27.326 --> 00:28:27.926 A:middle
playground.

00:28:31.196 --> 00:28:32.486 A:middle
Once you've done this you'll

00:28:32.486 --> 00:28:34.196 A:middle
want to ship all of your types,

00:28:34.196 --> 00:28:35.636 A:middle
and your values, and your API to

